		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Aragorn vs. the Nazgul<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.61)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=3300'>Ryan "Shadow 13" French</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=3300&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 13, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> If you&#39;re a major Lord of the Rings fan like me, you&#39;ve probably read the &quot;Lord of the Rings in 10 minutes&quot; script.  There&#39;s one interesting part of it that goes like this:<br />
<br />
  Nazgul: Bwahahaha! Give us the ring, little worm!<br />
  Frodo: Sticks and stones may break my bones, but names-- <br />
  Sam: Hmm, looks like swords work too. <br />
  Strider: Go away, bad men! <br />
  Nazgul: The five of us must flee, for we are outnumbered <br />
    by this one Ranger!<br />
<br />
This is of course the Weathertop scene, where Aragorn quite heroically chases off five Nazgul.  Not only does he chase them off, he completely defeats them in combat.  Pretty amazing feat for a mere ranger...but it&#39;s not actually possible in a game, is it?<br />
<br />
Actually, it is.  And I&#39;ll show you how.<br />
<br />
This article isn&#39;t going to be a serious discussion of the strategy of the game, but I do hope to alert you to an amazingly powerful combo that all too often is overlooked or summarily ruled out because players assume (and have actually told me in deck reviews), &quot;That can&#39;t possibly be legal.&quot;  But I&#39;ve checked every aspect of this deck, and it&#39;s legal, baby.  The actual situation I&#39;ll draw up may be a little far-fetched, and definitely very lucky, but it&#39;s certainly possible.  And it should give you some ideas about the power of certain cards.<br />
<br />
First off, we&#39;ll bid 2.  Our opponent bid 1, so we go first.  Great.  We drop our first site: The Prancing Pony.  After all, we&#39;ve got to get Aragorn out somehow, and this is the easiest.  We play Frodo and the Ring.  Any combination of Frodos and Rings will do.  And our starting Fellowship: Merry Friend to Sam and Boromir Son of Denethor.  For those of you unfamiliar with names, that&#39;s Rare Merry and Uncommon Boromir, the meanest engine in the game.  Why?  Because it is perfectly legal, and I&#39;ve asked Elrond@decipher.com to make sure, to increase Merry&#39;s strength and then exert him twice to add his strength into another skirmish.  You just can&#39;t increase his strength after you add it to another skirmish, and expect that to have any result.<br />
<br />
So now we draw our hand.  Surprisingly, it&#39;s all Free Peoples cards.  We&#39;ve got Elrond and his daughter Arwen, a Ranger&#39;s Sword and a Dagger Strike to go with it, Celeborn, and three Stout and Sturdy&#39;s.  We&#39;ll need those Stout and Sturdy&#39;s to heal Merry during skirmish phases so we can add his strength into another skirmish twice, that&#39;s why there&#39;s four of them in the deck.  So looking at our hand, we&#39;ll deploy the elves (adding 8 to the pool), exert Elrond four times (healing him once with Celeborn) to draw four cards, carefully obeying the card-drawing Rule of Four.  We get all Free Peoples cards again: a Flaming Brand, a Council of Elrond, a Saga of Elendil, and an Elendil&#39;s Valor.  We&#39;ll drop that Saga on Boromir and add 1 to the pool, for a total of 9.<br />
<br />
Well we&#39;ve got all Aragorn&#39;s cards, so let&#39;s play him from our deck.  We add a burden and 4 to the pool to drop Aragorn, Ranger of the North out of our deck, then play his sword and a brand on him, adding 1 to the pool, so it&#39;s up to 14 now.  Now we play Council of Elrond to grab There And Back Again and drop it on Merry, adding 3 more to the pool.  There&#39;s 17 twilight in the pool now, and we&#39;ve played everything we could, so let&#39;s exert Celeborn again to heal Elrond (so a Tower Assassin or twilight Attea can&#39;t kill him), and move.<br />
<br />
Our opponent&#39;s site is the Weatherhills, so we add 8 more to the pool, giving him a total of 25.  Little do we know that this is just enough for our opponent&#39;s amazing god-hand: all four Twilight Nazgul plus Ulaire Nertea...the five Nazgul who were actually at Weathertop (ok, I can&#39;t prove Nertea was there, but he looks a lot like the one that got a brand through his head), plus The Master&#39;s Will and two Morgul Gates.  Thanks to the site all those Nazgul play for -1, and he&#39;s thinking he just might be able to get them all down.  He decides to go with the big guys first; so he plays Morgul Gates twice to get the Witch-King and Enquea down for a total of 12, leaving him another 13 tokens to work with.  He plays Attea for 7 (killing Celeborn and leaving 6), and then decides to try out The Master&#39;s Will.  He included it in his deck for that &quot;perfect&quot; situation, and this looks like it could be the one.  He removes 1 from the pool, leaving 5, and draws the top three cards...two of which are Shadow cards, and both of those are Morgul Gates.  Talk about luck.  So with those two Morgul Gates he plays Nelya and Nertea for the last 5 twilight, and announces that Nelya is fierce and damage +1 thanks to our three burdens.<br />
<br />
Maneuver phase.  We&#39;ll start by playing Elendil&#39;s Valor, and then we exert him three times to get him up to defender +4.  Our opponent figures we plan to let Aragorn go out with a bang.  Little does he know...next we discard There And Back Again, boosting Merry to 5 power until we regroup.  That&#39;s it for maneuver.  Nothing happens during archery, so we assign all five Nazgul to Aragorn and our opponent is wondering why we decided to drop There And Back Again when Boromir could easily deal with the one fierce Nazgul.<br />
<br />
Skirmish phase for Aragorn.  Our opponent is about to exert his Witch-King and Enquea in victory when we play Dagger Strike.  Now Aragorn is strength 15 and damage +3.  Hardly impressive, since the Nazgul total is 56, damage +1.  Now we turn to Merry.  He&#39;s already power 5, so let&#39;s exert Boromir three times to add 9, making him 14.  We exert him twice to add 14 to Aragorn, so the contest is now 29d+3 vs. 56d+1.  We play two of our Stout and Sturdy&#39;s, and exert Merry two more times.  By the way, from here on out we&#39;re not going to worry about adding twilight because the Shadow player has no cards left in his hand and no special abilities to use until he wins a skirmish.  Our opponent is beginning to wish he&#39;d drawn The Nine Servants of Sauron first...Aragorn&#39;s total is now 43d+3.  We play our last Stout and Sturdy, exert Merry two more times (exhausting over half of our companions), and now Aragorn is 57d+3.  57 to 56...Aragorn wins.  And since he&#39;s damage +3, every Nazgul takes four wounds, enough to kill them all.  Of course, he payed a stiff price: Merry, Boromir, and Aragorn are exhausted now, and during the regroup phase the Shadow player drew eight more cards, while our hand is empty.  Dare we move on?  Probably not...let&#39;s just glory in our hard-fought victory!<br />
<br />
So maybe that movie scene isn&#39;t so far-fetched after all.  In the game, Aragorn can knock off five Nazgul at once.  How did he do it?  By using the Uncommon Boromir and Rare Merry combo.  The point of this combo is to win skirmishes, because if you win every skirmish, a lot of nasty Shadow cards never get used.  Orc Banner and Gleaming Spires Will Crumble come to mind immediately.  Also, dead minions don&#39;t fight in fierce skirmishes; you only have to deal with them once.  <br />
<br />
While this combo does cost a lot in exertions, you&#39;ll find that healing those exertions isn&#39;t too difficult.  Using Athelas x4 takes care of Boromir, and Farmer Maggot plus Rare Frodo, not to mention the new Silverlode site from Mines of Moria, will help out Merry.  And of course you should pack a few extra copies of each character for even more healing.<br />
<br />
Of course, Merry alone won&#39;t help you win every skirmish.  Blade of Gondor is a must for helping out Boromir, plus perhaps a couple Last Alliance of Elves and Men if you go with the Elrond drawing engine.  Swordarm of the White Tower is an excellent strength booster for both Boromir and Aragorn, especially with Rare Aragorn and Elendil&#39;s Valor.  Swordsman of the Northern Kingdom is fairly good if you see a lot of Uruk-Hai or Sauron Orcs, but I prefer Sentinels of Numenor with all the Balrogs flying around these days.  Then don&#39;t forget Hobbit Stealths and Intuitions, but also don&#39;t forget that some players will tech against stealth events and might get around those.  Also, I should mention that this Merry combo does have major problems with one decktype: Moria Swarm.  Elendil&#39;s Valor x4 plus Rare Aragorn will help you control the number of minions on Frodo, but a couple PATHS are required in this deck.<br />
<br />
There&#39;s one more important aspect of the deck to cover, and that&#39;s the speed at which you move.  With a lot of strength bonuses in this deck, plus the Merry combo, you can generally double move without major problems.  However, your opponent can often do the same if you don&#39;t concentrate on your Shadow side to the same degree.  So what I like to do is run 4xRare Aragorn, bid to go first, and start the Green Dragon Inn to pull Sam.  I drop my extra burdens on Sam and use him as a pincushion on my first move.  If by some crazy chance he makes it to Rivendell safely, I heal him up, take on more burdens, and save him as a snack for the Balrog.  By removing the Prancing Pony from the game, you establish early control of Fellowship movement against players who rely on it for getting Aragorn out.  Conversely, if you don&#39;t end up going first, you weren&#39;t relying too heavily on your first site to help out your Fellowship; rather you were simply using it to slow down your opponent.  And chances are, a high-bidding player is going to start the Green Dragon Inn to get Sam out fast, so you&#39;ll still be in the same boat.<br />
<br />
That last tip was free...I didn&#39;t actually plan on putting it in here, but it should help you with your Merry deck.<br />
<br />
Well, I hope that through this simple illustration I helped you see the power of this unlikely combo.  My brother ran a deck much like this one, starting Green Dragon Inn and running 4 Aragorn&#39;s, and took first place in a multiplayer tournament with it.  This style has merit...try it yourself.<br />
<br />
Ryan French<br />
Rebel Strike Team founder<br />
http://www.decktech.net/43<br />
Rider of Rohan<br />
